  "description": "Narrator is the voice that tells the story. The narrator is not the author — even in first person, the narrator is a construct, a made thing with particular knowledge, limitations, attitudes, and blind spots. Wayne Booth clarified this through the concept of the implied author: the reader infers a sensibility behind the narrator\u0026rsquo;s choices that is distinct from both the narrator and the real author [@booth1961].\nNarrators vary along several dimensions:\n",
